This contributes to the following Country Programme result: 1. By 2020, women, infants and young children in Bangladesh, especially the most disadvantaged (with disabilities or living in urban, remote and disaster-prone areas), access and utilize high-quality social services in a safe environment, and their families are empowered to practise positive behaviour.

description.narrative: UNICEF showcased a successful approach to resolving water quality problems in Bangladesh by implementing the “Arsenic Safe Union” model. This success prompted the Government to invest $240 million to scale up the model. Moreover, UNICEF extended strategic technical support to Dhaka North City Corporation, which renders municipal services to more than six million inhabitants, to develop a ‘climate-resilient and safe sanitation services roadmap’ aiming at conserving the environment and freshwater bodies. Furthermore, in rural sanitation, support was provided to communities to climb the sanitation ladder and access safe services that satisfy SDG-6 quality standards. | Status:Met | As-of Date:22/12/2021
